            <h3>Painkillers</h3>
            <p>One of the early focuses of medicine was to treat the pain that often came with disease. Opium was first used in Europe in the 1500s to treat pain and was later also made into laudanum. The first modern pharmaceutical medicine, morphine, was invented in 1804 by Friedrich Sertürner, who extracted the main active chemical from opium. While morphine was effective against severe pain, opium-based treatments were addictive and thus not ideal. Paracetamol was first synthesised in 1893 and aspirin in 1897, providing effective and common non-narcotic treatments for mild to moderate pain and fever. Paracetamol is considered the safest common pain reliever as overdose is unlikely when taking normal doses and side effects are rare compared to other non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs). Aspirin used to be commonly taken pain relief and is still used to prevent blood clots and heart attacks, but is otherwise not recommended for regular use due to its increasing patients' risk of bleeding and gastrointestinal upset.</p><br />
