            <h3>Antibiotics, Antivirals and Antiparasitics</h3>
            <p>One of the first modern drugs used to treat infections was quinine in 1820, which kills malaria parasites. Antiparasitic drugs are needed to treat a range of infections including worms, protozoans and external parasites. In 1928, the first antibiotic, penicillin, was accidentally discovered with mould growing on a Petri dish of bacteria, and was later used to treat a wide range of bacterial infections. This eventually led to the discovery of more classes of antibiotics by research companies, treating all kinds of infections. In 1963, the first antiviral, idoxuridine, was used to treat herpes virus infections of the eye. Antiviral drugs for a range of other viral infections like influenza and HIV were also developed, generally for the severe infections. Currently, new antivirals can treat a range of diseases, like remdesivir, a broad-spectrum antiviral which is effective against Covid-19.</p>
