            <h3>Antihistamines</h3>
            <p>Allergy is a common condition when the body has an immune response to harmless substances like dust and pollen, or food allergens like peanuts, or insect bites. The immune response causes inflammation at the supposed infection sites to draw in immune cells, using histamine messenger molecules. Antihistamines can treat this by blocking histamine receptors, preventing or reducing the severity of histamine-mediated immune responses. The first synthetic antihistamine, piperoxan, was developed in the 1930s, and is an alpha-adrenergic antagonist that stop certain cell receptors from triggering an immune response. While first generation antihistamines cross the blood-brain barrier and cause drowsiness, the more modern second generation antihistamines only target specific body receptors and do not affect the brain or cause drowsiness. Different types of antihistamines have different effects and choosing the right one often depends on the individual and symptoms.</p>
            <br />
            <h3>Cough Medication</h3>
            <p>Cough medicine is a common medication that is used to relieve symptoms, though studies suggest cough medication may not actually reduce the severity or duration of coughing. Expectorants like guaifenesin allow mucus to move out of the throat, antitussives like pholcodine suppress the urge to cough, mucolytics like bromhexine thin mucus to make clearance easier, antihistamines and nasal decongestants can also be used in cough medicines. The main benefit of cough syrup is likely the syrup itself, which can reduce inflammation and irritation when covering the throat, rather than the active ingredients. Honey is also a natural alternative to cough syrup, with studies finding it works well against dry cough. Throat lozenges can relieve irritation of the throat but do reduce the duration or severity of cough.</p>
