            <h3>Chemotherapy</h3>
            <p>The first methods of treating cancer involved surgery and radiotherapy, which were only temporarily effective as traces of cancer cells were frequently left behind to form new tumours. This started to change in the 1940s, when nitrogen mustard was found to cause tumour regression, though also temporary, then later folate antagonists like methotrexate were used to suppress leukaemia cell growth. Some antibiotics like actinomycin D were also found to have antitumour ability, while other drugs like fluoropyrimidine 5-fluorouracil (5-FU) specifically targeted abnormal cancer cells more than normal body cells, resulting in targeted therapies with less adverse side effects. A major breakthrough came in the 1960s when a combination of different chemotherapy drugs were used to cause a complete remission of cancer, instead of a temporary remission with just one drug. This was later extended to combine drugs with surgery and radiotherapy to maximise cancer cell death in treatments. While chemotherapy has continued to progress, major disadvantages of chemotherapy still include drug toxicity affecting normal cells, a suppressed immune system causing more frequent infections and reduced cell growth causing problems like bleeding. Modern cancer research has started to look at the immune system rather than chemicals, finding ways to help immune cells kill cancer more effectively and directly.</p>
            <br />
            <h3>Exercise</h3>
            <p>Regular exercise has been found to naturally prevent diseases including cancer, for a range of reasons including improving the immune system, reducing the number of hormones involved in cancer development, reducing inflammation and insulin levels, and preventing obesity, a risk factor for a range of diseases.</p>
